'''

When to Use Which?
Use gather() when

You want:

result1 = ...
result2 = ...
result3 = ...

and need all results before continuing.

Example:

await asyncio.gather(
    fetch_users(),
    fetch_products(),
    fetch_orders()
)
Use create_task() when

You want background execution.

Example:

asyncio.create_task(send_email())

Return response immediately:

return {"status": "success"}

Email continues in background.

Can They Be Used Together?

Absolutely.

task1 = asyncio.create_task(fetch_user())
task2 = asyncio.create_task(fetch_orders())

results = await asyncio.gather(
    task1,
    task2
)

gather() can wait on tasks that were created with create_task().
Interview-Friendly Summary
Feature	create_task()	gather()
Starts coroutine	✅	✅
Runs concurrently	✅	✅
Returns immediately	✅	❌
Waits for completion	Only when you await task	Immediately
Multiple coroutines	Possible but manual	Designed for it
Returns results	One task result	List/tuple of results
Background jobs	Excellent	Not suitable
Parallel API calls	Possible	Best choice
Mental Model
asyncio.create_task()

= "Start this work and I'll decide later when (or whether) to wait."

await asyncio.gather(...)

= "Start all these works now and don't continue until every one of them finishes."

'''
